    {
      "id": "edaa0e8bb2e93997903a07001d15855c20ddd446",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-01-21 16:54:18.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nGood commit comment. I also like the change to use an array for the counters instead of listing each one. \n\nSince you are modifying every OSD_DECLARE_OP() line anyway, you may as well make the new function name lower case instead of ALL CAPS like a macro. \n\nI still don't understand how OSD_EXEC_OP() makes sense. This will allow any operation to have 2x as many operations as declared. That will avoid serious errors, but not the more common off-by-one error.\n\nRather than automatically using the rollback credits as soon as the normal credits are gone, I think it makes more sense to have some kind of flag for the OSD that we are now in rollback mode and credits should be available for that. One option is to only increase the rollback credits as each normal operation is done, so that they will not be available before the normal operation.\n\nFor example, if the rb credit counter is only incremented in OSD_EXEC_OP() then this prevents using credits before they actually need to be rolled back. If OSD_EXEC_OP() sees that there are no more normal operation credits for some type, then it could set a flag in the thandle that it is in rollback mode and only credits from the rb array can be used.  If there are no rb credits for the operation type, then the original operation was never done, or it is a case of missing the declare. \n\nThis avoids changing the API, but doesn't allow the credits to be used if there is a coding error in most cases.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
